What superfoods should I be eating? Acai? Spirulina? Collagen? 

The truth is… 

There really is no such thing as a “super” food. Of course, there are certain whole foods that are more nutritionally-dense and offer unique health-promoting properties, but ultimately there is no “superfood” that will be the sole cause of a transformed healthy life. 

There is not a single food or supplement that will alter your health in a significant way exclusive of your overall diet and lifestyle. What matters the most is what you consistently do on a day-to-day basis. 

If you focus on healthy eating and sustainable habits, you’ll find your optimal health in the long run. 

Plus, who wants to eat collagen? 🤢

🌱 💚 With Leafy Green Love,
Julieanna Hever

7 Simple Meal-Planning Strategies ✍️

Here are some of my tried-and-true meal-planning tips for making cooked-from-scratch meals a daily reality, even after the most exhausting days. Back when my kids were growing up and I was in the midst of the classic juggling act, I learned to be a lot more disciplined about meal planning. I found that it really did buy me time and my sanity!

So whether you’re a classic juggling parent, a corporate 
professional, an entrepreneur, an electrician, a musician, or anything and everything in between, these strategies can be applied to any lifestyle or profession, and it works!

(1) Plan 3 full meals each week.
(2) Plan meals before going shopping.
(3) Plan meals after going shopping.
(4) Prepare a few basics for the week ahead.
(5) At least once a week, prepare a big one-pot or one-pan meal.
(6) Develop a weekly repertoire.
(7) Create a seasonal repertoire.

If you are a seat-of-the-pants kind of cook, more power to you!  For that kind of spontaneity, you’ve got to have a well-stocked pantry and fridge, and a big imagination! However you operate in your home, any or all of these strategies can only help add to your cooked-from-scratch tool kit.

Please share any of your tips and tricks for staying on top of your meal-planning so we can all stay on track with our health goals and lifestyles, and hold each other accountable!

🌱 💚 With Leafy Green Love,
Julieanna Hever

Curious about intermittent fasting or time-restricted feeding?

In recent years, time-restricted feeding has become a popular way of eating. And for very good reason.

What is it? Time-restricted feeding is a way to incorporate the health advantages of fasting in an effortless way. There are many ways to do this, but one version is to isolate your eating window to a few hours out of the day and keep your body in a fasted state for the rest of the time.

Why is it good for you? In the fasted state, your body has the chance to take care of important metabolic housekeeping - helping your body to rejuvenate, restore, and refresh.

But don’t fall into the trap that many do! 

Just because you are sticking to a time-restricted feeding schedule doesn’t mean that you can eat whatever in those hours reserved for meals. It’s even more important to make sure you are nourishing your body with healthy, wholesome foods.

🌱💚 With leafy green love, 
Julieanna Hever

You are NOT broken. It is ALWAYS the food. 

Our bodies have evolved over many centuries to SURVIVE. And when  food was not available all day, every day, and we were gathering berries - we developed some primal instincts. We didn’t know when the next meal was going to be coming so our bodies learned to store calories to keep us alive.

5 Ways to Avoid Cardiovascular Disease, without Medication!

Cardiovascular disease is the number 1 killer of both men and women globally, killing approximately 17 million people each year, according to the World Health Organization.  While the American Heart Association and the American College of Cardiology have recently released new guidelines for cardiac prevention that emphasizes the prescription of statins, diet is one of the most critical and often ignored components to heart and vascular health.  And it doesn’t have the potentially serious and uncomfortable side effects like memory loss, liver damage, increased risk of type 2 diabetes, and muscle damage that statins have.

There are NO negative side effects to eating a heart-healthy diet.  Only benefits like weight management, healthy digestive function, and increased energy.

Here are 5 easy ways to avoid cardiovascular disease without the harmful use of prescription medication:

(1) Make at least half of your diet fruits and vegetables.
(2) Minimize saturated at intake.
(3) Eat a high-fiber diet.
(4) Mind your (food-sources of) B-vitamins.
(5) Exercise consistently.

Avoiding heart disease doesn’t have to be complicated with the use of prescription medicine.  It can be as easy as consuming a plant-based diet, plus exercise!

So many times people want to skip the things that are actually good for you!

I’ve been seeing a recent upsurge in popularity for green drinks. As a registered dietitian, I can’t help but tell you it’s all a little silly.

We have so many amazingly incredible sources to get our nutrition - and you lose a lot of that by putting it into “powder” greens. One of the most important components of fruits and veggies - fiber - gets eliminated. 

There is no “get healthy quick” hack that I can give you. There is a way to get healthy, sustainable, and simply.

But it’s not through powdered greens. 

It’s through progressing with small changes to your diet and lifestyle. 

Maybe you are still eating animal products right now, but you’re starting to add more fruits and veggies. 🍒🥕🥬

Maybe the next step is to switch to whole foods, while still having some animal products. 

Maybe after you get comfortable with that, you can start to eliminate animal products.

Take your health journey like stairs - one step at a time.

Here’s a little throwback to me explaining to @steveharvey what a plant-based diet is. One way to put it is I don’t eat “anything with a mom or a face” 😂

But what does plant-based actually mean?

You may not know this, but I was the OG "Plant-Based Dietitian" and wrote one of the first books with the title that included the term, "Plant-Based Nutrition."

It all evolved as the data kept aggregating showing that eating more plants appeared to be the most health-promoting, disease-fighting diet.

Here are a few common questions and answers about Plant-Based Diets.

Is “plant-based” the same as “vegan”?

A vegan diet is an exclusive definition - meaning one does not eat animal products. A plant-based diet is an inclusive definition that means one eats a diet based on vegetables, fruits, whole grains, legumes, mushrooms, nuts, seeds, herbs, and spices in infinite tasty combinations (👈 that list, tho, says it all). 

Where can I get protein on a plant-based diet?
The original source of protein is not animals - it's PLANTS!

Plants contain all of the amino acids that make up the building blocks for the myriad proteins your body makes. Seeds, legumes, nuts, quinoa - and so many more delicious treats- are fantastic sources of amino acids that could sustain even an athlete. ⛹️‍♂️

What are some of the benefits of a plant-based diet?
A plant-based diet is the only that has been shown to actually REVERSE advanced-stage cardiovascular disease and type 2 diabetes and is associated in the literature with reducing risk for most chronic diseases and conditions. ❤️

Anecdotally, in my experience of being “The Plant-Based Dietitian” for over 17 years, I've seen people shed weight, reverse chronic illness, get off their medications, and so much more.

When you give your body the tools it needs to do it's job, the extraordinary results are typical 🙌🏼🌱💚

Wanting some at-home comfort food?

This is a delicious, warming, and nutritious soup that you can whip up quickly. Core ingredients? Potatoes! You know I love potatoes - they are full of so much nutritional value and really help with satiety signals. 

You’ll definitely feel satisfied after eating this soup. 😘

Creamy Potato Corn Chowder 🌽🥔🙌🏼

Ingredients:
1 medium yellow onion (~3 cups), diced
2 celery stalks (1 1/2 cups) , chopped
2 medium carrots (~1 1/2 cups), peeled and chopped
1 green bell pepper, seeds and ribs removed, chopped
4 garlic cloves, minced
4 cups low-sodium vegetable broth, divided
4 medium Yukon gold potatoes (~4 cups), cubed
2 cups frozen corn
1 bay leaf
1 tsp ground black pepper
4 tbsp chopped fresh dill
3 tbsp low-sodium tamari
2 cups plant milk

Directions:
1. Heat a large saucepan or Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Once hot, add onion and dry sauté until brown. Add as little water as possible to avoid burning but to allow browning on the bottom of the pan, until onions are translucent.
2. Add in celery, carrots, bell pepper, garlic, and approximately one cup of the broth and sauté for 5 minutes, until vegetables begin to soften. Stir in potatoes, corn, bay leaf, black pepper, and dill. Bring to a boil. Once boiling, reduce heat and simmer over medium heat until the vegetables are soft, approximately 15 to 20 minutes.
3. Pour in tamari and plant milk, bring back to a boil, and cook for an additional 5 to 10 minutes. Turn off heat and remove bay leaf. With an immersion blender, puree the soup until most if pureed, but some remains chunky, to your preferred texture. Cook until thickened, 5 to 10 minutes. Serve hot.

7 Ways to Save Money on a Plant-Based Diet.

A common concern about eating a plant-based diet is that it is expensive. Yet, there are ways to purchase food on any type of meal plan that range widely from simple to extravagant, regardless of whether there are animal foods in the mix or not. In fact, you will likely save thousands of dollars (or more) in healthcare expenses by eating a wholesome plant-centered diet. 

Here are 7 ways to do that:

(1) Buy foods that have a longer shelf life in bulk.
(2) Shop local farmer’s markets for fresh, local, seasonal fruits and vegetables.
(3) Minimize or avoid processed and convenience foods at the grocery store.
(4) Cook more often.
(5) Prepare.
(6) Never shop hungry.
(7) Try growing your own food.

There is misunderstanding around how easy a plant-based diet can be.  I hope this helps clear up some of the confusion or uncertainty. As always, please comment below or DM me should you have any questions!

Around the holidays, there’s a lot of advice coming around from “health experts.”

One of them that I would like to squash is the idea that “carbs are bad for you.”

This idea has persisted for years, perpetuated by the Atkins diet and was carried on by its successor, the Keto Diet. 

Though many people can lose weight by “cutting carbs,” they aren’t bad for you. You can lose weight by omitting entire macros or food groups or in any way that creates a caloric deficit. But that does not make it a healthy diet. 

In fact, carbs are essential to a healthy diet. It just depends on where you are getting them from. The world’s most health-promoting, disease-fighting foods - veggies, fruits, legumes, whole grains - are high in carbohydrates. 

However, when you refine them into flours, sugars, and all of the processed foods that are devoid of fiber, vitamins, minerals, and phytonutrients, then they can cause issues. The carbs from a lentil stew are quite different from the carbs found in a candy bar. 

As always, when you enjoy a whole food, plant-based diet, focusing on the most wholesome ingredients possible, carbs are not at all a problem. 

🌱💚 With leafy green love,

Anyone else have this reaction to restaurant food before? 😂

Compared to 10 years ago, it’s much easier to find healthy options at restaurants now, especially if you live in a major metropolitan area. 

But still, eating out can sometimes be challenging when you are following a whole food, plant-based diet…especially if avoiding oil, other highly processed ingredients, or if you have intolerances or allergies.

Have you seen those menus with zero vegetable options before? Or the ones where veggies can’t be prepared without being doused in cream, butter, or oil?

The great news is that you CAN eat out while staying true to your eating parameters:

(1) Choose the most user-friendly restaurant.
e.g. try to go to a plant-based location

(2) Play detective with the menu.
Make sure to take a look through the whole menu! I often find hidden gems for a delicious meal in the appetizers or side dishes sections.

(3) Specify the prep method.
Avoid fried foods and ask for your meals to be prepped either baked, steamed, grilled, or sautéed.

(4) Charm the waitstaff.
They can help you on the menu and also try to work with the chefs.

(5) Plan in advance.
Find your compromise between being a happy customer and also getting your needs met. Be polite and offer/ask for suggestions from the staff on what to eat.

Feeling good, inside and out 🙌🏼

Eating a plant-based diet isn’t just about reducing risk for chronic disease, mitigating symptoms from chronic conditions, reducing medication requirements, and losing weight. There are myriad of ways in which plants can heal us, but one we don’t talk enough about is - mood.

Now, I love a good glass of wine, but when we are looking at weight loss, there are three ways alcohol disrupts the process.

1) It Must Be Metabolized Immediately!

Our body has to metabolize the alcohol first since we have no storage capacity for it. That means any additional calories after that cheers is more easily stored as fat. 

2) It Stops the Fat Loss Process!

Why? Because alcohol is in your system and being metabolized for 4 to 6 hours after the last swallow. During that time frame, your body is not metabolizing body fat. 

3) Alcohol Lowers Our Inhibitions

We all know that alcohol lowers our inhibitions and discretion can dissolve, making it way easier to say yes to foods that aren’t on plan and interrupt our progress. 

There’s nothing wrong with a little indulgence every once in awhile, but these are some things to think about when it comes to weight loss and alcohol.

Carbophobia is real. People worry about eating carbs. But if you ask someone what a carb is, they often don’t know the answer. That’s because even researchers and healthcare practitioners are confused. 🫤

For example, potato chips contain more calories of fat per gram than carbohydrates (306 kcal fat vs 215 kcal CHO per 100 grams). 

There are studies that conclude that both low carbohydrate consumption and high carbohydrate consumption increase mortality risk….in the same study! How is anyone to make sense of this, let alone make practical decisions based on this conflicting information? The answer is that it is a waste of time, energy, and resources. 

Or swipe through to see the nutrition facts on 100 grams of baked potato vs 100 grams of a doughnut, both considered “carbs”. They both contain a similar amount of carbohydrates. But, if you dig deeper, you’ll find that the doughnut is almost half fat and half carbohydrate, but the doughnut’s carbohydrate comes predominantly from sugar. This is a giant conundrum if you are trying to tell people to eat fewer carbs or less fat. It is far simpler, clearer, and more accurate to say “eat more starchy vegetables and fewer refined baked goods.”

Finally, foods high in carbs are some of the most health-promoting foods on the planet. A diet based on vegetables, fruits, whole grains, legumes, mushrooms, nuts, seeds, herbs, and spices in infinite tasty combinations offer the two most  vital nutrients for health - fiber and phytonutrients. 

🔆Takeaway points:

1. Don’t fear carbs.
2. Opt for whole foods - potatoes over chips, whole grains over refined flour products, fruit over candy.
3. Fiber - found in carb-rich foods such as legumes and veggies - is crucial for optimal health.

Happy 89th Birthday to the “Father of Modern Nutrition,” Dr. T Colin Campbell!

I dubbed him the “Father of Modern Nutrition” many years ago because Dr. Campbell pioneered a path in nutrition science that changed the trajectory of how we understand nutrition and our health today. 

- He coined the term “whole food, plant-based” 
- He described why whole matters
- He persisted on paving the path despite everyone - all the naysayers - around him

He started his research career under the premise that we need to consume more protein. But, because of what he discovered, he changed his perspective. His ongoing research revealed that high intakes of protein - especially sourced from animals - is not only unnecessary but actually contributes to the promotion of chronic disease. Going against the grain - especially when it conflicts with your worldview - takes great courage and resilience. And that is what changes the world.

Macroconfusion 🤔🤷🏻‍♀️

The number one cause of nutrition misinformation boils down to macroconfusion. Even researchers and healthcare professionals struggle to make sense of nutrition when the lens are these biochemistry terms used to describe food.

Here is an excerpt from The Choose You Now Diet detailing this issue:

There are 3 energy-containing macronutrients found in our food (well, 4 if you include alcohol) - fat, carbohydrate, and protein. While these are biochemistry terms used for classification, they have been misused and misinterpreted in the last several decades, confusing everyone from people trying to understand what exactly they should eat to researchers trying to distill science and physiology into useful recommendations. 

The evidence on an ideal macronutrient profile for a diet for weight loss or for health is inconclusive. There is evidence showing that both a higher fat diet is healthful, a la the Mediterranean diet, and that a low-fat diet, such as that studied in Okinawa, Japan, is optimal. There are also studies that conclude that both low carbohydrate consumption and high carbohydrate consumption increase mortality risk….in the same study! How is anyone to make sense of this, let alone make practical decisions based on this conflicting information? The answer is that it is a waste of time, energy, and resources. 
 
Secondly, both a baked potato and a doughnut would be classified by many as a “carb.” This is because they both contain carbohydrate. But, if you dig deeper, you’ll find that a very different profile (swipe left to see the deets). This is a giant conundrum if you are trying to tell people to eat fewer carbs or less fat. It is far simpler, clearer, and more accurate to say “eat more starchy vegetables and fewer refined baked goods.��

One concern many people have about eating healthy is the time investment.

But there is a way to make it SUPER SIMPLE!

Batch cooking 🙌🏼👩🏻‍🍳

Batch cooking is a cost- and time-efficient way to prep food for days at a time. Here is how to do this:

1. Find one day a week when you can shop for all your fresh ingredients.
2. Pick a time slot of maybe 2-3 hours, once or twice a week.
3. Plan what you will make and write lists of ingredients you will need before you shop. Maybe keep a recipe organizer so you can just pull them up as needed. 
4. Make everything all at once. Enjoy and store the rest in airtight containers the fridge for 4-5 days.
5. Repeat.

My favorite foods to batch cook each week include:

- Baked potatoes (sweet, purple, Japanese, Yukon gold, russet, fingerling…)
- Huge salad
- Delicious dressings in jars on the side
- Soup, stew, chili, chowder
- Hummus
- Stir-fried veggies
- Beans, lentils, tofu, tempeh 
- Casseroles, curries
- Lasagna, loaves
- Veggie burger patties
- Filling for tacos, tostadas

So many things! You can even double batch and freeze for longer-term storage.

“We are what we repeatedly do. Excellence, then, is not an act, but a habit.” -Will Durant

Everything you want to do begins with a thought. A decision. The next step is evolving this decision into a goal. Once you have your desired goal(s) in place, you need to set up a system to execute on these goals. Decide all of the details on what it takes to achieve them and how can you implement and weave this practice into your every day life. Turning this goal into reality requires choosing small steps or habits and then practicing, practicing, practicing until they become automatic.

As @jamesclear writes in his bestselling book “Atomic Habits,” the four steps to setting a new habit are: make it obvious, make it attractive, make it easy, make it satisfying.

Research varies vis a vis a conclusion on how long this takes to become automatic - from 21 days all the way to just under a year. Ultimately, the longer you repeat the habit, the more concrete it becomes.

Some tips to building and maintaining new habits:

- Start small, make them easy to achieve
- Minimize any friction or obstacles (e.g. if you are trying to not eat cookies, avoid having them in your home)
- Stay patient 
- Consistency is everything
- Use all the accountability possible (e.g. if you are trying to lose weight, maintain a food journal, get on the scale daily, seek social support)

Success is simply a series of successive small victories. And those successes are made over many moments throughout the day. Every day. You get to choose to serve your purpose. You get to choose again and again and again. You get to choose you now. - from The Choose You Now Diet

What IS Time-Restricted Eating (TRE)? 🕚

- A version of intermittent fasting (IF)
- It is allowing time in the fasted state necessary for metabolic housecleaning
- It is not actually fasting

There are myriad health benefits to time-restricted eating related to our circadian clocks. TRE (with or without calorie reduction) has been associated in some pilot trials with weight loss, and improvement in glucose intolerance, hypertension, and high cholesterol levels. 

While TRE may be socially abnormal or extreme, it is biologically normal and beneficial. 

Practical use of TRE includes:

- Maintain a consistent window of eating/fasting
- Avoid eating 1-2 hours after waking and 2-3 hours before going to sleep
- Choose healthy, wholesome foods when you are eating 
- Consider a multivitamin to cover your micronutrient bases 

⚠️ Of course, as always, check with your healthcare provider about whether TRE is appropriate for you, especially if you are currently on medications. ⚠️

Nature is perfectly imperfect. Or imperfectly perfect. It’s chaos and order, complexity and simplicity. 🌿🍃 🦋

But a diet?

There is no such thing as a perfect diet. 🦄

It doesn’t exist. Even the idea of getting 100% of daily recommended intakes of all macro- and micronutrients is not necessarily “perfect.” Even if it were, most anyone could not achieve that anyway, especially every day. 

All the recommended numbers and serving sizes are based on averages. Think of all the variables that make your body unique to you - your size, activity levels, muscle mass, current goals, lifestyle, preferences, genetics…you do not need the same servings of the same foods and nutrients as everyone else. There is room for interindividual variability. 

There is also no perfect macronutrient ratio. 🦄

It doesn’t exist. The healthiest populations in the world have been on both low- and high-fat diets. This is why there is so much debate. 

Instead of trying to be perfect, chasing an unrealistic and unnecessary idealistic diet, aim for these basic dietary goals that are well-established to be healthful:

🌈Eat rainbows every day. Each color in your food represents different categories of health-promoting, disease-fighting nutrients.

🫐Eat foods as whole and intact, as minimally processed as possible. Fruit instead of juice, whole grains instead of flour, nuts or avocado instead of oil. 

🍽️Remember that less is more. Remaining in the fed state (which continues 4-6 hours after your last swallow) is energetically and metabolically taxing on the body. Time in the fasted state offers your body an opportunity to take care of all the other necessary metabolic housecleaning. 

“Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication.” - Leonardo Da Vinci 🦋🌟💫🌿🍃

Legumes include all the vast varieties of beans, lentils, peas, hummus (which should be a food group), and soyfoods such as tofu and tempeh. This category is crucial for so many reasons including these:

1. Legumes are a rich source of essential amino acids and fibers, including resistant starch, soluble, and insoluble. 
2. They are high in the minerals iron, calcium, zinc, magnesium, phosphorus, potassium, and manganese, as well as B vitamins (especially folate), and phytonutrients, including isoflavones, flavonoids, lignans, lutein, and zeaxanthin. 
3. Consuming legumes has been positively associated with optimized weight management, decreased risk for cardiovascular disease by lowering blood lipids, improving vascular function and insulin sensitivity; type 2 diabetes via better glycemic control; and certain cancers via powerful anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects.
4. Legumes are the #1 longevity food according to the Blue Zones data.
5. They are very inexpensive, shelf stable, and easily accessible.

Chipotle Chili from The Choose You Now Diet 🌶️🍅❤️

This smoky, hearty tofu chili can be made in advance and enjoyed in different ways throughout the week over the fries, baked potatoes, atop spaghetti squash, cauliflower rice, or cooked greens, or even as a salad “dressing” topper. 

INGREDIENTS:
1 small (~1 cup) red onion, chopped small
1/2 medium (~1/2 cup) green bell pepper, chopped small
1 jalapeño, chopped small
2 garlic cloves, minced
2 tbsp chili powder
2 tsp ground cumin
1 tsp coriander
1 tsp Mexican oregano
1 tsp ancho chili powder
1 tsp smoked paprika
1 (16-oz) package extra firm tofu, crumbled
1 (15-oz) can kidney beans, rinsed and drained
2 cups strained tomatoes
1/2 cup tomato paste
2 chipotle peppers in adobo sauce, chopped small
3 tbsp adobo sauce from can of adobo chipotle peppers
1 tbsp low-sodium tamari
1 tsp liquid smoke
1 1/2 cups low-sodium vegetable broth

DIRECTIONS:
1. In a large, heated saucepan or Dutch oven, dry sauté the onion until onions are translucent. Add enough water or broth to keep from completely drying out, but don’t let them swim in liquid. Add jalapeño and bell pepper and cook until vegetables soften, about 2 to 3 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add garlic, chili powder, cumin, coriander, Mexican oregano, ancho chili powder, and smoked paprika, and sauté for 60-90 seconds, being careful to brown, but not burn. Add tofu, kidney beans, tomatoes, tomato paste, chipotle peppers, adobo sauce, tamari, liquid smoke, and vegetable broth and bring to a boil.
2. Once boiling, reduce heat to low, cover, and simmer for 30 minutes, or until thick. Adjust seasonings as desired.
3. Serve immediately with the chili spooned over Air-Fried Potatoes (see video below in my feed) and drizzled with cheesy sauce (see video below) or store separately in airtight containers for up to 5 days.

My Favorite Vegetable 🤍

I 🤍 cauliflower! It is very versatile, very tasty, and extremely nutritious, as a cruciferous vegetable. In fact, one of the healthiest food groups on the planet are cruciferous vegetables. Cruciferous consumption protects against cardiovascular disease, metabolic disorders, obesity, diabetes, and cancers, and it offers antimicrobial and anti-aging activities, and more. Their benefit comes partly because they contain a potent antioxidant, anti-inflammatory compound called sulforaphane. When cruciferous vegetables are cut, chopped, or chewed, an enzyme myrosinase converts these compounds into the active anticancer form, isothiocyanates. Myrosinase is deactivated by heat, so try chopping the greens and allowing them to sit for a few minutes to allow the reaction to take place before cooking. A healthy hack is to add mustard powder, wasabi, or daikon radish to cooked cruciferous vegetables to initiate this reaction, since they contain myrosinase. 

Included in this category are broccoli, Chinese broccoli, broccoli rabe, Brussels sprouts, cauliflower, kale, collard greens, bok choy, cabbage, kohlrabi, mustard, turnip, radish, watercress, wasabi, daikon, and arugula. 

Enjoy at least three servings a day of these foods, where one serving is equal to 1 cup raw or 1⁄2 cup cooked. 

Some of my favorite ways to enjoy them include:

 🥦 As cauliflower rice raw in salads, cooked as a nutrient-dense replacement for rice
🥦 Shredded cabbage, kale, broccoli in salad
🥦 Bok choy, broccoli, and cabbage in stir-fries, soups, curries

Savoring 🧡

We often associate the concept of savoring with taste and eating. Yet, we can also engage all five of our senses to fully savor the world around us. For example, savoring a beautiful sunset with our eyes, an inspiring piece of music with our ears, petting an animal’s soft fur with our fingers, and the sweet smell of a rose with our nose. 

Savoring can be defined as the process in which people engage ‘to attend to, appreciate, and enhance the positive experiences in their lives’. Research has shown that individuals who savor positive events in their daily life evidence a greater boost in happy mood as a result. (Bryant and Veroff, 2007) 

In my work with clients and in my personal journey, I have been focusing on the concept of savoring in order to generate more presence, to enhance the experiences in our unpredictable, rapidly-paced lives. 

Some of my favorite ways to practice savoring are:

🔸Lighting scented candles in the evening. 
🔸Putting down my phone to focus in on conversations and experiences. 
🔸Enjoying hot baths with lavender-scented soaps. 
🔸Taking slow, mindful walks outside. 
🔸Listening to music.
🔸Keeping flowers in my home and stopping to enjoy their scent and visual beauty whenever I walk by. 
🔸Practicing mindful eating by setting the environment, focusing in, slowing down, and truly tasting each bite.

🔁 Our bodies are inextricably linked to the day-night, monthly, and seasonal cycles. 

🕦 So many biological processes are impacted by circadian clock that you may not be aware of, including: fat accumulation, insulin secretion, insulin sensitivity, Immune function, cardiovascular function such as blood pressure, vascular tissue, food absorption, and other intestinal functions. We are impacted down to the cellular level and most of us don’t even pay attention to this important biological function. 

🕦 Circadian Clocks govern many processes in the body and may significantly contribute to the accumulation of age-related chronic disease.

Here are 5️⃣ ways to optimize chronobiology: 

1️⃣ Proper sleep hygiene. Get 30 minutes of bright light in the morning to help anchor your circadian clock. In the evening, turn off screens at least an hour before bed. Go to sleep in a dark, cool room and don’t use excessive blankets. Melatonin supplementation may be helpful for you, particularly if you’re over 40, and it seems to also be a strong sirtuin activator. 🥱

2️⃣ Avoid eating at least 3 hours prior to bedtime. This will improve your sleep so you can maximize that crucial time for your body and brain. 🤐

3️⃣ Eat at the same times every day to avoid hunger throughout the day. 🍽️

4️⃣ Exercise consistently - ideally at the same times each day. 🧘🏻‍♀️

5️⃣ Manage your caffeine intake. Use and schedule your intake based on your known sensitivity to caffeine. ☕️
